On Fri, Jan 24, 2020 at 1:14 PM Devon Klein <yaypatrol@hotmail.com> wrote:

> Dear loved ones,
>
> I realize that with the impact on my capacity of all this recent struggle,
> I have not been great at consistently communicating with you all about my
> efforts to address things. So, I thought it would be worthwhile to send a
> group update.
>
> First, I'll start with the good news. Returning to the structure, purpose
> and successful engagement of my work has caused a small reduction in my
> symptoms. I have been focusing the bulk of my energy on engaging with this
> issue and have found some benefits from acupuncture, contact with my
> sponsor, (moderate) physical activity and meditation practice. I am
> continuing to work with my doctor and have returned to seeing my previous
> counselor who specializes in PTSD.
>
> The "bad" (really more frustrating) news has to do with my attempts to
> engage specialists. I originally received two referrals through my doctor,
> from there I was referred on to six more potential services. I have been in
> contact with a LOT of people and found that most programs did not have
> availability until mid-february, so eagerly took an intake that was
> available for 1/13. Sadly, at that meeting I was recommended for
> hospitalization but without much explaination of why this was necessary. I
> expressed concern about missing work and created a plan for combining
> weekly outpatient counseling with dietician meetings.
>
> After a lot of communication and requests for information, I got an
> appointment with the dietician, but was told that the counselors waitlist
> is "several months" long. In conjunction with my doctor, we explored the
> Intensive Outpatient Program as an alternative in hopes of getting
> counseling more quickly. Not only is this difficult to navigate (three
> hours daily, seven days a week means I don't have the ability to start
> until late February), but there doesn't seem to be an option for any
> counseling services prior to that. Additionally to this, at my first
> meeting with the dietician on 1/22, I was told that they'd be recommending
> that I abstain from all exercise.
>
> I am currently seeking a second opinion at the encouragement of my doctor,
> counselor and sponsor because I am not feeling heard currently in wanting
> to use a strengths-based approach. I have been reminded that I have agency
> within my own care. I keep being told to stop using my current healthy
> coping strategies. Specifically I consider the best/healthiest parts of my
> life to be my work that provides structure, purpose and meaning; my regular
> movement practice, especially running, dancing and yoga and my
> connections/being of service within my recovery community. I am seeking a
> program wherein I can continue in work, some reduced or moderate movement
> practice and spending time with my sober supports. My fear is that if I
> give up too many of my healthy habits, I will eventually resort to
> unhealthy ways of coping and I don't need any more of those.
>
> Last but not least, as you know my birthday is coming up next month. I am
> looking forward to celebrating in a variety of ways both my 43rd navel
> birthday and my 2nd sober birthday. I do not in any way expect any gifts as
> we're all adults. If, however, you feel so moved I am seeking a few things
> for my new home. I need to replace the pots and pans I lost in my last
> move, I would like a fruit bowl and I'd like more black and white family
> photos (maybe of my adorable nephews - hint!) for my family photo wall. The
> parental unit are coming to visit me for lunch on 2/9, I have a restaurant
> in mind that we could visit together. I welcome visits from any of you all
> who would like to see my little corner of south Seattle. I am hoping to
> purchase tickets shortly to go see the NYC family and celebrate together.
>
> I am sorry for the lengthy message, but I wanted to be thorough. Please
> feel free to ask any questions that you have and I'll try to be more
> consistent in my communication going forward. I'm so grateful for the love
> and support from each of you. I'm truly blessed to have you in my life.
>
> Love,
> Devon
>

